  "style": "APA",
  "texts": [
    "Referring to polling results presumably yields a massive advantage over referring to the judgment of an acquaintance in one's neighborhood: polls express the aggregate preferences of various demographics.",
    "The new possibility of fine-grained predictions allows voters to know with more accuracy the aggregate opinions of the demographic they identify with.",
    "To be sure, cues can also be autonomy-undermining, if they are unreliable and followed blindly.",
    "A classic example of unreliable cues is the Search Engine Manipulation Effect (SEME) (Epstein and Robertson 2015), where experimental evidence finds the ranking of search-engine results can marginally change vote choice depending on their valence.",
    "So if you, a potential voter seeking to be more informed about the upcoming election, type the words 'Donald Trump' in a search engine, your preferences may marginally change if the first link amongst the results presents the candidate in a positive light, as opposed to negative."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
    "A classic example of unreliable cues is the Search Engine Manipulation Effect (SEME) (Epstein and Robertson 2015), where experimental evidence finds the ranking of search-engine results can marginally change vote choice depending on their valence."
  ]
